  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Meyer's NT Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 15:40-41",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "Ἐπιλεξάμενος Σίλαν",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "after he had chosen Silas",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " as his apostolic companion. It is accordingly to be assumed that Silas (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 15:27",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), after he had returned to Jerusalem (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 15:33",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), and had along with Judas given an account of the result of their mission, had in the meantime returned to Antioch. But the interpolation, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 15:34",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (see the critical remarks), is incorrect, as the return of Silas to Jerusalem was a necessary exigency of the commission which he had received. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ἐπιλέγεσθαι",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", in the sense ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "sibi eligere",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", only here in the N.T.; often in Greek writers, the LXX., and Apocr.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "παραδοθ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "τῇ χάρ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "τ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "Κυρίου",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "committed to the grace of Christ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (see the critical remarks). Comp. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 15:11",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Not different in substance from ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 14:26",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", but here expressed according to a more specifically Christian form. Moreover, the notice, compared with ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 15:39",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", leads us to infer, with great probability, that the church of Antioch in the dispute before us was on the side of Paul.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "τὴν Συρ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "κ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "Κιλικ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".] as Barnabas (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 15:39",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), so Paul also betook himself to his ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "native country;",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " from their native countries the two began their new, and henceforth for ever separated, missionary labours. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Barnabas",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " is unjustly reproached (by Baumgarten) with repairing to his own country, instead of to the wide fields of heathenism; in point of fact, we know not the ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "further",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " course which he adopted for his labours.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Expositor's Greek Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 15:40",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "Π",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "δὲ ἐπιλεξ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "Σ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".: not in the place of Mark, but in the place of Barnabas, Ramsay, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "St. Paul",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", p. 171; having chosen, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "i.e.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", for himself: ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "sibi eligere",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; only in N.T. in this sense, but in classical Greek and in LXX, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Samuel 2:28",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " A, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Samuel 10:9",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " R, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Sir 6:18",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1Es 9:16",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1Ma 1:63",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " R, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 5:17",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", etc.; “elegit ut socium, non ut ministrum” (Blass). If Silas had not returned to Jerusalem, but had remained in Antioch (see above on ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 15:35",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), he had doubtless recommended himself to Paul by some special proof of fitness for dealing sympathetically with the relations of the Jewish Christians and the Gentile converts. This sympathy on the part of Silas would be the more marked and significant as he was himself almost certainly a Hebrew; otherwise we cannot account for his high position in the Jerusalem Church, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 15:22",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", although his Roman citizenship is implied in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 16:37",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; perhaps this latter fact may account for his freedom from narrow Jewish prejudices. If we may identify, as we reasonably may, the Silas of Acts with the Silas (Silvanus) of the Epistles, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Corinthians 1:19",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Thessalonians 1:1",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Thessalonians 1:1",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Peter 5:12",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", the last mention of him by St. Peter becomes very suggestive. For St. Peter’s First Epistle contains the names of the two men, Mark and Silvanus, who had originally been members of the Jerusalem Church, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 12:12",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 15:22",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", and moreover the two oldest of St. Paul’s associates, whose brotherly Christian concord had been broken for the time (when Paul chose the latter in the place of Barnabas, and rejected Mark’s services altogether), but who are now both found at St. Peter’s side in Rome (assuming that Babylon is Rome), evidently at one with him and with each other; the one the bearer of a letter, the other the sender of greetings, to ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Pauline",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " Churches. If St. Paul had passed to his rest, and the leader had thus changed, the teaching was the same, as the names of Silvanus and Mark assure us, and St. Peter takes up and carries on the work of the Apostle of the Gentiles, see Dr. Swete, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "u. s.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", pp. 87, 88.—",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ἐξῆλθε",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "cf.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
